recently I’ve been moved by the thought that in jiu jitsu I can create anything I dedicate myself to. like for example, right now I’ve been focused a lot on improving my guillotine. I think it’s something that I always had a feeling I wasn’t good at. that makes me work on my headlock, which is one of the ways of getting guillotines. I’ve been thinking on ways to get there as an attack or as a counter attack.

we are actually working on this at @gbnorthridge right now. I think that besides bringing to my students something valuable, something I’ve chose to spend my time with, I also help myself to improve. more that they know about that position, better is our training, and more options I have to get better.
as a teacher, I should be happy if I get caught with a position that came from an idea I brought up, and helped someone to figure out something. 
as a fighter, I should be happy to get beat by a position I couldn’t come up with myself. 
I believe my potential is measured by how many times I put myself in vulnerable situations and comeback stronger from it.

next thing I want to focus on, are the guillotine set ups from the guard, like Marcelo, Kron and Roger.

another week of a lot of jiu jitsu. very grateful for the life I have. seriously! to do everyday something that I love in an environment such as @gbnorthridge @kingsmma_hb @graciebarra_hq it’s a blessing!

it’s when you let things go with the flow that you realize what the flow is…

front head lock escape

you gonna roll to the opposite side of the underhook. use that movement to push opponent away and pull yourself up. sit up pushing the free elbow against the ground. to sit up don’t do it on a straight motion, but rather on a semi circle trajectory (that will be the lightest and easiest way to come up). as you start sitting up, transition your arm into a strong frame to keep opponent away. the last part of the position is crucial to avoid an armbar: shake your arm off to push opponent away as you come up on your knees. 
remember to attack right away 😈

this weekend I had 2 fights with the same opponent at the @ibjjf San Diego Open. it was a bracket of 3 but the other guy didn’t show up. I submitted him in the first fight and won by advantages in the second one. my opponent was game and he was able to follow the pace but I felt technically superior in most of exchanges we had. this one in the video is the perfect example… it was in the second fight and I felt like a step ahead of him in the whole scramble. I believe I would be able to secure the back if for some reason there was no out of bounds. 

to be honest I was training like once a day for this tournament plus some conditioning some days. I’m 32 years old now so I feel I kinda have to control the rhythm of my training a little more, and I believe that the tournaments ahead in the next month will be more important so I wanna peak there. but I’m always training and I like to go hard and to get better so I will always be ready to show up no matter what. next month I will be sharp af tho! I know that. I’m really excited to put the work honestly! 

thanks @gorilla_hands for the corner 🤘🏾

one of the positions we worked in class last night at @gbnorthridge // 🎥 @liviagocruz

when I was color belt and in the beginning of my black belt days(more like years actually), my game was a lot based on having 1 or 2 strong passes and trying to build all of my offense on top of that. I wouldn’t say I had a lot of success with it, meaning that from 10 out of 9 times it would work. it was more like 5/10 and the only other times that I would win besides that was from fighting for life to maintain top position because really I had no confidence in my guard. that way of training and fighting was on the way of my own flow. that brought me a lot of ref decisions… aka boring matches. that kept me away from living to my full potential as a fighter. and definitely not that much fun to be honest.

fast forward… I worked tirelessly on my guard at @gbnorthridge with many many hours having my guard brutalized by @romulobarral 😑 some days I didn’t want to go to training. many days rather. but I would and that built my resilience in a way like nothing else ever did. tapping hundreds of times to the same guy is something that is heavy on the ego. making the decision to face this feeling purposely is like jumping on a dark abyss that you know that somehow will be good for you. that shit is DARK tho… and painful. but I made it to the other side and it’s way more fun now actually, almost 18 years later. jumping on the dark and then allowing myself to create my own way of doing it, were huge factors of how I see jiu jitsu now.

going back to the beginning of this post… it was important to have those 2 strong guard passes but it was just as important to know when to let go of it and move on to the next move (maybe I can do a post later to say what I think about that… when is the right time to move the focus to the next position in jiu jitsu).

I haven’t trained with Rominho in a while but I’m sure still sucks lol. // i’ve been training a lot with the scramble king @oliverthedentist aka thefbidentist. and just as cool as experiencing my own progress is to see my friends getting better too… keep it up bro 👊🏾

thank you @liviagocruz @gbnorthridge for the video ⚡️

1. all the transitions in the very beginning are intended to find some space to get closer to the hips. I will go through a couple of checkpoints before I get there. the first thing I have to deal with when my opponent is playing some kind of open guard with the back on the ground are the legs. I need to find some space to get either in between or around the legs. once I have one of my legs inside I have to make sure I’m always out leveraging or clearing out his hooks so he doesn’t move me around. with no rush, I’m also purposely putting myself in all kinds of positions (while staying safe) to feel where I can have a clearer path. the whole time I make connection with the top frames (arms) I need to weigh down on it. putting pressure on the top frames is one of the most important things to deal with a really good guard, that you might only be able to pass overtime.

2. controlling the back of the head with one arm and the top leg(shin) with the other is a very solid control when you get to the hips. but I need to be ready to post on the ground every time I get out of balance and he is trying to get under like at the part 2 of the video.

3. at this part he is able to get the hook inside to try to elevate but my head control and my body position make really hard for him to deal with and I can easily control the top leg.

4. the legs are not as much of a threat anymore and I decide to try to move up towards side control. the top frames are still in place but Jack is out of position, which makes easier for me to go around it and stabilize side control.

5. Jack is one of the hardest training partners I ever had to control a position on him. he always finds a way to move out like here on 5. that shit is exhausting (I hope he doesn’t really read this post). training with him is getting me so much better in controlling positions and thinking on what to do next.

6. the back is probably the best position he is at escaping. so here I shoot my hook to the far hip keeping it as tight as possible because I know he will try to clear it right away. constantly attacking the head and arms is really important so he doesn’t have both arms free to escape.

🎥 @liviagocruz

this video is from the last time I drove to Joshua Tree to have some time alone and organize my thoughts. I love to be by myself and think about my life.

one of the many reflections I had that day was to be grateful for the people that have supported me throughout my journey. I thought about it for some time and I realized that sometimes is also time to let some of them go. that’s because some will support the person I am today but not so much the one I want to become. the one I can become. as hard as it is I can’t let anything on the way of my growth. 

sometimes what happens is that the “old me” set my standards lower than what I deserved and it might be a little too uncomfortable for some to realize it and accept that I want to change. but that’s ok! I might have done the same with others too. 

life goes on…

in my nogi classes at @gbnorthridge I incentivize everyone to train with everyone. I believe that that’s one of the secrets to build a solid room of training. 

as a more advanced grappler, it might feel as a waste of time going with someone less skilled. but I believe that that’s one of the most important things in martial arts: to get out of your way to help the school you’re part of to grow. 

the reason that I chose this video to say that, is that Eddie, the one training with me in the video, trains for less than 2 years. I believe if he keeps doing what he is doing he is gonna become a great grappler. I enjoy training with him because his attitude of not really caring of who he is going against but more focused in trying to win positions.

of course, there is so much more progress to be made. as fast as you learn, you can only get better so much at a time. but I think that for me as a teacher is important to try to recognize the progress of my students from all stages, or at least I like and try to. 

another important factor that is so important as someone that is starting, besides finding a good place to train, is definitely on being humble. I think when you’re humble more people will try to help you on the way. the more everyone is trying to help you, faster you improve. and by being humble I don’t mean accepting and allowing people to disrespect you. but by trying to understand your place in the school and acting accordingly.

9:30pm in LA // after my last match I realized that I needed to put a lot more focus on my wrestling. the rules of my last fight wouldn’t allow pulling to guard for 3 minutes and we had to wrestle. I honestly felt like getting a little tired in our wrestling exchanges and that affected me during the rest of the fight. 

to be honest after I decided to stop mma training last year and got my focus back to jiu jitsu I got super lazy with my wrestling, and if I couldn’t really take someone down in like 20 seconds I would just pull guard. in mma, as a grappler, you don’t have that option. you have to wrestle. I remember that my wrestling got so good in 2020 when we were just wrestle these kids at Benny’s gym and after some time I was feeling confident to exchange takedowns even with the more experienced guys. but this last year my takedowns got a little rusty, and now it’s time to fix that for december, where my wrestling will need to be sharper than ever. 

soon I will have some very exciting news to share about my next super fight in december, but I still can’t say much. all I can say is that I will be all day at @gbnorthridge starting next week…

I want to develop more that idea in my classes of the importance of top half guard in jiu jitsu. it’s a position that you can really control your opponent once you’re there. it allows you to set good grips and find better positioning from a safe spot before or while setting up a submission.

very disappointed with the performance I had last night. but as @felipepena said in the video he posted, there are things you only really notice on defeat. now it’s time to get up and rebuild. head high. props to my opponent that was the better fighter last night.

thanks @ufcfightpass for the opportunity in this awesome show. I know people are talking about the rules, but as an athlete that competed on those rules and lost lol, I think the rules force action and it’s more entertaining for the person that doesn’t know jiu jitsu. so if we really gonna grow jiu jitsu, why not? and of course like any set of rules, there’s adjustments that need to be made like in any process of finding a final great project. 

best thing of the weekend was to receive so many supporting messages before and after the fight. I really appreciate all of you my friends ♥️ I mean it! 

special thank you to everyone that was there with me this weekend! we will get back better!
